I think you can use `java.util.properties` to solve your problem; to write to your properties first create a new `Properties` object, [`load`][1] them via your `InputStream`, use methods such as `setProperty` to add to your configuration and finally use [`store`][2] to write to them.

Example:
```
File appConfig = new File(&quot;a_file&quot;);
FileInputStream propsInput = new FileInputStream(&quot;a_file&quot;);

Properties prop = new Properties();

prop.load(propsInput);

try (Writer inputStream = new FileWriter(appConfig)) {

   // Setting the properties.
   prop.setProperty(&quot;A_PROP&quot;, &quot;A_VALUE&quot;);

   // Storing the properties in the file with a heading comment.
   prop.store(inputStream, &quot;INFORMATION!!!&quot;);

} catch (IOException ex) {
   ex.printStackTrace();
}
```


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Properties.html#load(java.io.InputStream)
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Properties.html#store(java.io.OutputStream,%20java.lang.String)

